Browser Environment & Specs:
-----------------------------
JavaScript runs not only in browsers — it can run in many environments (Node.js, Deno, etc.). The browser environment adds extra features to work with webpages — like window, document, alert(), etc.
Code:
alert("Hello Browser!"); 
console.log(window.innerWidth); 

window is the global object in browsers — contains everything.
document - represents the webpage (DOM).
navigator - gives info about browser.
location - gives current URL.
Browser adds these as “extras” to JavaScript.

Specs:

ECMAScript (ES) - defines the core JS language.
DOM (Document Object Model) - defines how JS interacts with HTML.
BOM (Browser Object Model) - defines browser-related objects (window, navigator, etc.).

DOM tree:
---------
The browser converts your HTML into a DOM tree — a structured tree of nodes (elements, text, comments).
<html>
  <body>
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <p>World</p>
  </body>
</html>

Becomes:
Document
  html
      head
      body
          h1
          p

Note:
Every tag = Element Node
Text between tags = Text Node
The root of everything = document

Walking the DOM:
----------------
moving through DOM elements — parent → child → sibling.

let body = document.body;

console.log(body.firstElementChild); // first child
console.log(body.lastElementChild);  // last child
console.log(body.parentElement);     // parent node
console.log(body.previousElementSibling); // previous node

childNodes - list of all child nodes (including text).
children - only element nodes.
firstChild / lastChild - first/last node.
parentNode - go up one level.
nextSibling / previousSibling - move sideways.


Searching Elements:
------------------
Find elements in the DOM.
document.getElementById("myId");
document.getElementsByClassName("item");
document.getElementsByTagName("p");
document.querySelector(".class");
document.querySelectorAll("div.item");

querySelector() -	First match -	CSS selector
querySelectorAll() -	NodeList -	All matches

Node Properties: Type, Tag, and Contents:
----------------------------------------
Each DOM node has basic info — type, name, and content.
nodeType ->	1 = element, 3 = text, 8 = comment
nodeName / tagName ->	Node’s name (uppercase for elements)
innerHTML	-> HTML inside element
textContent	-> Text only (no HTML)

Modifying the Document:
-------------------------
You can create, remove, or move DOM elements dynamically.

let div = document.createElement("div");
div.textContent = "Hello!";
document.body.append(div); // add to page

Styles and Classes:
------------------
Can edit element style or class list directly.

let box = document.querySelector(".box");
box.style.backgroundColor = "lightblue";
box.classList.add("highlight");

Coordinates:
------------
Each element has coordinates relative to the viewport or document.

let rect = elem.getBoundingClientRect();
console.log(rect.top, rect.left); // element position
